body:
@davidmascharka Two problems with `PYTHONHASHSEED`:
1. We shouldn't touch global python flag (at least not by default) that changes behavior of other user code and other imported libraries.
2. Even if we use `PYTHONHASHSEED`, it only controls `str`, `bytes` and `datetime` objects. Other things like user defined hash functions still can't be controlled.
